\par \pard\plain \s28\qj\sb0\sa283\qc\sb0\sa0\ltrpar{{\*\bkmkstart TRUE_BUTTERFLIES}{\*\bkmkend TRUE_BUTTERFLIES}\rtlch \ltrch\b\loch
THE TRUE BUTTERFLIES}
\par \pard\plain \s28\qj\sb0\sa283\qc\ltrpar{\rtlch \ltrch\scaps\b\loch
Superfamily}{\rtlch \ltrch\b\loch
 }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\b\loch
Papilionoidea}
\par \pard\plain \s28\qj\sb0\sa283\qj\sb0\sa283\ltrpar{\loch
The great suborder of butterflies is commonly separated into two principal groups called superfamilies. One of these includes all of the higher butterflies and is named }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\loch
Papilionoidea}{\loch
. The other includes the lower Skipper butterflies and is named the }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\loch
Hesperioidea}{\loch
. The former are characterized by small bodies and relatively large wings, straight clubbed antennae, and the fact that the caterpillars do not make cocoons when preparing for the chrysalis state.}
\par \pard\plain \s28\qj\sb0\sa283\qj\sb0\sa283\ltrpar{\loch
The most authoritative classifications of butterfly families are based upon the peculiarities of wing venation and are admirably discussed in such books as Holland's "Butterfly Book" and Comstock's "How to Know the Butterflies." Without attempting to go into the technical details of structure it will suffice here to give the list of families which compose the superfamily }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\loch
Papilionoidea}{\loch
:}
\par \pard\plain \s28\qj\sb0\sa283\qr\ltrpar{\loch
The Parnassians. }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\loch
Parnassiidae.}{\loch
\line The Swallowtails. }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\loch
Papilionidae.}{\loch
\line The Whites, Orange-tips, and Yellows. }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\loch
Pieridae.}{\loch
\line The Nymphs. }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\loch
Nymphalidae.}{\loch
\line The Satyrs or Meadow-browns. }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\loch
Agapetidae.}{\loch
\line The Heliconians. }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\loch
Heliconidae.}{\loch
\line Th}{{\*\bkmkstart Page_56}{\*\bkmkend Page_56}\rtlch \ltrch\cf17\loch
[Pg 56]}{\loch
e Milkweed Butterflies. }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\loch
Lymnadidae.}{\loch
\line The Long-beaks. }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\loch
Libytheidae.}{\loch
\line The Metal-marks. }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\loch
Riodinidae.}{\loch
\line The Gossamer-wings. }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\loch
Lycaenidae.}
\par \pard\plain \s28\qj\sb0\sa283\qj\sb0\sa283\ltrpar{\loch
It must not be thought that such a list necessarily indicates the degrees of development of the respective families, for this is not true. It is simply a linear arrangement adopted for convenience by leading authorities, notably Dr. Harrison G. Dyar in his standard "Catalog of American Lepidoptera."}
\par \pard\plain \s28\qj\sb0\sa283\qc\sb0\sa0\ltrpar{{\*\bkmkstart PARNASSIAN_BUTTERFLIES}{\*\bkmkend PARNASSIAN_BUTTERFLIES}\rtlch \ltrch\b\loch
THE PARNASSIAN BUTTERFLIES}
\par \pard\plain \s28\qj\sb0\sa283\qc\ltrpar{\rtlch \ltrch\scaps\b\loch
Family}{\rtlch \ltrch\b\loch
 }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\b\loch
Parnassiidae}
\par \pard\plain \s28\qj\sb0\sa283\qj\sb0\sa283\ltrpar{\loch
It is perhaps a bit unfortunate that the group of butterflies, which is commonly chosen to head the list of families, is one that is rarely seen by most collectors. The Parnassians are butterflies of the far north or of high elevations in the mountains. The four species credited to North America have been collected in Alaska and the higher elevations of the Rocky Mountains, so there is very little probability of any of them being found in the Eastern states.}
\par \pard\plain \s28\qj\sb0\sa283\qj\sb0\sa283\ltrpar{\loch
While, structurally, these butterflies have a close affinity with the Swallowtails, one would never suspect it from their general appearance. Their bodies are large and all of the wings well rounded, so that there is more of the suggestion of a large moth than of the Swallowtail. The coloring is also more moth-like than with most butterflies, the wings being very light colored and nearly transparent, with markings of gray and brown, arranged in dots and splashes.}
\par \pard\plain \s28\qj\sb0\sa283\qr\ltrpar{\loch
All our species belong to the genus Parnassius. The }{{\*\bkmkstart Page_57}{\*\bkmkend Page_57}\rtlch \ltrch\cf17\loch
[Pg 57]}{\loch
 caterpillars show their affinity with those of the Swallowtails by having the curious scent organs or osmateria just back of the head. They feed upon such alpine plants as stonecrop and saxifrage and are well adapted by their structure and habits to the bleak surroundings of the mountain tops.}
\par \pard\plain \s28\qj\sb0\sa283\qj\sb0\sa283\ltrpar{\loch
As a typical example of the environment in which these butterflies live, we may take the alpine valleys of such mountain regions as Pike's Peak. Prof. M. J. Elrod has described a visit where, at an altitude of 11,500 feet in the month of August, }{\rtlch \ltrch\i\loch
Parnassius smintheus}{\loch
 was flying by thousands, and the earlier stages were so abundant that a water ditch had the surface covered as far as one could see with the dead or dying caterpillars. In such situations, where ice forms at night, and snow frequently falls by day, these butterflies develop apparently in greater numbers than almost any of our other species are known to do in warmer regions.}
